const a = [
  {"id":7273,"text":"Which of the following is used to measure pH?","explanation":"The **pH meter** is used to measure pH.\r\n\r\nA pH meter is an electronic device that determines the hydrogen ion activity in water-based solutions, thereby indicating its acidity or alkalinity. It essentially gauges the pH of a solution. The principal component of a pH meter is the pH electrode, which is immersed in the solution that is being measured. This electrode is sensitive to the hydrogen ion concentration and produces an electrical potential related to it. The pH meter then interprets this potential and displays a pH value. While pH scales provide a conceptual understanding of acidity and alkalinity, pH meters give a quantitative measurement. Other methods, like pH indicators, may change color in response to different pH levels, but for precise measurements, especially in a laboratory setting, a pH meter is the standard instrument of choice.","reference":"Chatterjea, M. N., and Rana Shinde. Textbook of Medical Biochemistry. 8th ed. New Delhi: Jaypee Brothers Medical Publications, 2012: 833.","responses":[{"text":"pH scale","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"pH color","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"pH electrode","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"pH detector","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"pH meter","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":7333,"text":"Which of the following correctly describes the first seven ribs?","explanation":"The first seven ribs are correctly described as **True ribs**.\r\n\r\nIn the human thoracic cage, ribs are categorized based on their attachment to the sternum. The first seven ribs, known as the true ribs, directly articulate with the sternum via their individual costal cartilages. This direct attachment ensures a stable connection between the ribs and the sternum, thereby providing protection to vital thoracic organs like the heart and lungs. Ribs 8 to 10 are referred to as false ribs because they do not have a direct sternal connection; instead, their costal cartilages connect to the cartilage of the rib above. Ribs 11 and 12 are termed floating ribs because they lack an anterior attachment to the sternum. Among the first seven true ribs, the first rib is atypical due to its unique shape and features, while ribs 2 to 7 are more uniform and are termed typical ribs.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 145.","responses":[{"text":"True ribs","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Floating ribs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"False ribs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Typical ribs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atypical ribs","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7351,"text":"During a tooth extraction procedure, a broken tooth accidentally fell into the respiratory passage. What is the most common site for the foreign body to dislodge?","explanation":"The most common site for a foreign body to dislodge in the respiratory passage is the **Right bronchus**.\r\n\r\nThe right main bronchus is wider, shorter, and more vertically oriented than the left main bronchus. Due to these anatomical features, aspirated foreign bodies are more likely to enter the right bronchus than the left. The direct path and steeper angle make the right bronchus a more probable site for inhaled foreign objects to become lodged. When foreign bodies like a broken tooth are accidentally aspirated, timely intervention is crucial to prevent complications such as atelectasis, pneumonia, and bronchiectasis. Radiographic imaging and bronchoscopy are commonly employed to locate and remove the foreign body.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 173.","responses":[{"text":"Bronchioles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trachea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Terminal bronchus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left bronchus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right bronchus","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":7518,"text":"Which of the following is the major component of surfactant?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 494.","responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cerebrosides","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gangliosides","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phosphatidyl lecithin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dipalmitoyl phosphatidylcholine","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":7733,"text":"What is the most common route carbon dioxide takes to be transported to the cells?","explanation":"The majority of carbon dioxide (CO₂) produced in the body's cells is transported to the lungs for elimination primarily **in the form of bicarbonate ions**.\r\n\r\nAfter being produced as a metabolic byproduct in cells, CO₂ diffuses into red blood cells. Inside the red blood cell, carbon dioxide reacts with water, catalyzed by the enzyme carbonic anhydrase, forming carbonic acid (H₂CO₃). This carbonic acid quickly dissociates into bicarbonate (HCO₃⁻) ions and hydrogen (H⁺) ions. The bicarbonate ions move out of the red blood cell and into the plasma in exchange for chloride ions – a process termed the \"chloride shift.\" In the lungs, the reaction reverses, liberating CO₂ to be exhaled. Approximately 70% of CO₂ is transported this way, making the bicarbonate ion method the most common route of CO₂ transport.","reference":"Hall, John E., and Michael E Hall. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier, 2020: 528.","responses":[{"text":"In the form of carbaminohemoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"In the form of bicarbonate ions","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"By dissolving in plasma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"By binding to plasma proteins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"In the form of carboxy hemoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7785,"text":"The phrenic nerve is accompanied by which of the following arteries?","explanation":"The **phrenic nerve** is typically accompanied by the **pericardiophrenic artery**.\r\n\r\nOriginating from the internal thoracic artery, the pericardiophrenic artery descends alongside the phrenic nerve, traveling in the thoracic cavity. Both the phrenic nerve and the pericardiophrenic artery provide supply to the mediastinal pleura, pericardium, and diaphragm. The close relation of the phrenic nerve to this artery is an anatomical concept often highlighted because of their shared course and because they are frequently seen together in medical imaging and during surgical procedures.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 226.","responses":[{"text":"Inferior epigastric artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Internal thoracic artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pericardiophrenic artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior epigastric artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Musculophrenic artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7800,"text":"A doctor performs a surgery at the superior border of the intercostal space, causing pain. Which structure is damaged?","explanation":"The structure located at the superior border of an intercostal space and most likely to be damaged during surgery in that region is the **intercostal vessels**.\r\n\r\nThe intercostal spaces house the intercostal neurovascular bundle, which includes the intercostal nerve, artery, and vein. These structures run in a specific order from superior to inferior: vein, artery, and nerve (often remembered by the mnemonic 'VAN'). When performing procedures in the intercostal space, it is imperative to remember that the neurovascular bundle lies near the superior edge, specifically to avoid injuring these structures. Damage to these vessels can lead to bleeding, while nerve injury can result in pain or sensory abnormalities.","reference":"Drake, Richard L. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Philadelphia, MO: Elsevier, 2020: 162.","responses":[{"text":"Intercostal vessels","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Epigastric vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intercostal muscles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemiazygous vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Azygous vein","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7806,"text":"The central chemoreceptors are stimulated maximally by which of the following chemical substance?","explanation":"The **central chemoreceptors** are stimulated maximally by a **high concentration of CO₂**.\r\n\r\nCentral chemoreceptors, located near the ventrolateral surface of the medulla oblongata, primarily sense changes in the pH of the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF). While these receptors are not directly sensitive to CO₂, an increase in CO₂ concentration in the blood leads to an increased diffusion of CO₂ into the CSF. Within the CSF, CO₂ reacts with water to form carbonic acid (H₂CO₃), which dissociates into bicarbonate ions and hydrogen ions. This process decreases the pH of the CSF. The resultant increase in hydrogen ion concentration is what stimulates the central chemoreceptors. Consequently, the primary driver for the activation of central chemoreceptors is elevated CO₂ levels, even though the receptors are technically responding to the associated change in pH.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 533.","responses":[{"text":"High concentration of bicarbonate ions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"High concentration of CO₂","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Low partial pressure of oxygen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"High concentration of hydrogen ions","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"High pH in blood","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7808,"text":"The students of first year MBBS are given a slide of the respiratory system. It shows all the usual layers: mucosa, submucosa, cartilage/muscular layer, and adventitia. Which of the following components of the respiratory airway has the greatest relative amount of smooth muscle?","explanation":"**Bronchi** are indeed characterized by a substantial amount of smooth muscle in their walls.\r\n\r\nThe respiratory system is organized as a branching network, and as we descend from the trachea to the terminal structures of the lungs, there's a variation in the histological makeup of these airways. Among them, the bronchi stand out for their significant smooth muscle component.\r\n\r\nWhile the trachea primarily relies on C-shaped cartilage rings for support, the bronchi, as they branch and reduce in size, exhibit more circular bands of smooth muscle. This arrangement of smooth muscle allows for the constriction and dilation of the bronchi, playing a crucial role in regulating airflow. Although bronchioles also contain smooth muscle, when assessing the relative amount of smooth muscle to the total wall structure, the bronchi have a more pronounced smooth muscle layer compared to other components of the respiratory airway.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 13th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2013: 350.","responses":[{"text":"Nasal cavity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Larynx","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bronchioles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trachea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bronchi","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":7832,"text":"Pleural effusion is checked on X-ray at which of the following levels?","explanation":"Pleural effusion, an accumulation of excess fluid in the pleural cavity, is best identified on an X-ray at the **costophrenic angle**. This angle is where the diaphragm (the primary muscle of respiration) meets the rib cage, specifically at the lateral-most aspect of the ribcage on a frontal chest X-ray.\r\n\r\nOn a normal X-ray, the costophrenic angles appear sharp. However, in the presence of a pleural effusion, these angles become blunted or obscured due to the fluid accumulation. This blunting is often one of the earliest radiographic signs of a pleural effusion. Lateral chest X-rays can also provide additional views of the costophrenic angle and further aid in diagnosis.","reference":"Chest x-ray abnormalities. Accessed May 20, 2023. https://www.radiologymasterclass.co.uk/tutorials/chest/chest_pathology/chest_pathology_page6","responses":[{"text":"Costophrenic angle","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cardiophrenic angle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sternal angle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Base of the lungs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Infrasternal angle","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7860,"text":"Which metabolic imbalance is seen in respiratory alkalosis?","explanation":"Respiratory alkalosis is characterized by a decrease in the partial pressure of carbon dioxide (PaCO₂) in the blood. This leads to a rise in blood pH due to a decreased concentration of hydrogen ions.\r\n\r\nOne of the significant metabolic imbalances seen in respiratory alkalosis is a decrease in the blood concentration of ionized calcium (hypocalcemia). This occurs because alkalosis causes an increased binding of calcium to albumin, thereby reducing the ionized fraction of calcium in the bloodstream.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, there can be a shift of potassium from the extracellular fluid into the cells, leading to hypokalemia.\r\n\r\nHence, in respiratory alkalosis, there are disturbances in both **Ca** and **K** levels.","reference":"(1) Lieberman, Michael, and Todd A. Swanson. BRS: Biochemistry, Molecular Biology, and Genetics. 6th ed. Board Review Series. Philadelphia, PA: Wolters Kluwer/Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins, 2014: 48. (2) Costanzo, Linda S. Physiology. 6th ed. Elsevier, 2018: 317.","responses":[{"text":"Na only","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"K only","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ca and K","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ca only","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ca and Na","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7948,"text":"Which of the following is a characteristic feature of the twelfth rib?","explanation":"The twelfth rib, also known as the last or the most inferior of the true ribs, has several unique anatomical characteristics that distinguish it from other ribs. Out of the provided options:\r\n\r\n- **Costal cartilage:** Every rib has costal cartilage, though the twelfth rib's cartilage is short and does not articulate anteriorly with the sternum.\r\n  \r\n- **Neck of the rib:** The twelfth rib typically lacks a neck.\r\n\r\n- **Angle of the rib:** The angle is not a distinguishing feature of the twelfth rib, as all ribs have angles.\r\n\r\n- **Single facet on head:** This is a **characteristic feature** of the twelfth rib. Unlike most other ribs that articulate with two adjacent vertebrae and have two facets (demifacets) on their heads, the twelfth rib only articulates with its corresponding vertebra (T12) and has a **single facet**.\r\n\r\n- **Costal groove:** Found on most ribs and is not unique to the twelfth rib.","reference":"Moore, Keith L., A. M. R. Agur, and Arthur F. Dalley. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Philadelphia: Wolters Kluwer, 2018: 76.","responses":[{"text":"Costal groove","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neck of the rib","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Single facet on head","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Costal cartilage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Angle of the rib","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":8020,"text":"Caseating granulomas are found in tuberculosis. This is an example of which type of hypersensitivity?","explanation":"In the context of tuberculosis, caseating granulomas are formed as a result of an immune response where the body attempts to wall off and contain the Mycobacterium tuberculosis bacteria. This specific immune reaction is an example of **type 4 hypersensitivity**, also known as delayed-type hypersensitivity (DTH), is cell-mediated and not antibody-mediated. T lymphocytes, particularly the CD4+ subset, play a critical role. It's this response that leads to the formation of caseating granulomas in tuberculosis.","reference":"Levinson, Warren, Peter Chin-Hong, Elizabeth A. Joyce, Jesse Nussbaum, and Brian Schwartz. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education, 2018: 559.","responses":[{"text":"Type 3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type 4","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Type 1 (delayed)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type 2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type 1 (immediate)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":8713,"text":"Which of the following sets of ribs exhibits the bucket handle movement during inspiration?","explanation":"During the process of inspiration, the ribs undergo two main types of movements: the pump handle and the bucket handle movement. The pump handle movement primarily involves the elevation of the sternum and is most pronounced in the upper ribs. The bucket handle movement refers to the upward and outward movement of the lateral aspects of the lower ribs, increasing the transverse diameter of the thoracic cavity. This movement resembles the motion of the handles of a bucket being lifted.\r\n\r\nSpecifically, the ribs that prominently exhibit the bucket handle movement are the middle ribs, as they have a greater range of movement in the lateral dimension compared to the upper and lower ribs. Thus, the correct answer is **Ribs 7 to 10**. These ribs increase the transverse diameter of the thorax, facilitating an increase in lung volume during inspiration.","reference":"Moore, Keith L., A. M. R. Agur, and Arthur F. Dalley. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Philadelphia: Wolters Kluwer, 2018: 81.","responses":[{"text":"Ribs 7 to 10","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Floating ribs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ribs 1 to 9","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Attached ribs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ribs 1-2","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":8773,"text":"A surgeon, while performing surgery, ligated the thoracic duct. Which of the following lymph drainage is not affected by this ligation?","explanation":"The thoracic duct is the major lymphatic vessel that drains lymph from most of the body back into the venous system. Starting from the cisterna chyli in the abdomen, it ascends within the thorax and empties into the junction of the left subclavian and internal jugular veins.\r\n\r\nThe thoracic duct receives lymph from the left half of the head, neck, and thorax via the left jugular, left brachiomediastinal, and left subclavian trunks. It also receives lymph from the diaphragmatic nodes, as well as from most of the abdomen, pelvis, and lower limbs.\r\n\r\nOn the other hand, the right side of the head, neck, and thorax, as well as the right upper limb, drain into the right lymphatic duct, which then empties into the junction of the right subclavian and internal jugular veins. \r\n\r\nHence, the **Right intercostal nodes** would not be affected by ligation of the thoracic duct, as these would typically drain into the right lymphatic duct or directly into the venous system.","reference":"Drake, Richard L. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Philadelphia, MO: Elsevier, 2020: 28.","responses":[{"text":"Diaphragmatic nodes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left parasternal nodes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left brachiomediastinal trunk","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right intercostal nodes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Left jugular trunk","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10096,"text":"Lungs are supplied by pulmonary and bronchial vessels. Which of the following blood vessels carries poorly oxygenated blood from the heart to the lungs?","explanation":"The heart pumps blood to various parts of the body through a network of blood vessels. The lungs, vital for the process of oxygenation of blood, receive blood supply through both the pulmonary and bronchial vessels. The **pulmonary arteries** are responsible for carrying poorly oxygenated blood from the right ventricle of the heart to the lungs. This deoxygenated blood travels via the pulmonary arteries into the pulmonary capillaries where it gets oxygenated. Following oxygenation, the blood returns to the left atrium of the heart via the pulmonary veins, now rich in oxygen. On the other hand, bronchial arteries provide oxygenated blood to the lung tissue itself, branching off the aorta. It's crucial to understand that it's somewhat counterintuitive: in the systemic circulation, arteries carry oxygenated blood, but in the pulmonary circulation, arteries carry deoxygenated blood to be oxygenated in the lungs.","reference":"Drake, Richard L. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Philadelphia, MO: Elsevier, 2020: 170.","responses":[{"text":"Bronchial veins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bronchial arteries","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary veins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary capillaries","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary arteries","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12092,"text":"The pump handle movement of the rib cage involves which of the following ribs?","explanation":"The respiratory movements of the rib cage facilitate the lungs' expansion and contraction during breathing. These movements involve both the elevation and depression of the ribs. Specifically, the \"pump handle\" movement describes the anterior-posterior increase in the chest diameter. It's akin to lifting the handle of a water pump: when the handle (anterior aspect of the rib) is raised, the other end (posterior aspect) moves more downward than outward. This movement increases the front-to-back diameter of the thoracic cavity, primarily due to the elevation of the sternal ends of the ribs. The ribs involved in the pump handle movement are primarily the upper and mid ribs, specifically **ribs 2 to 6**. These ribs have a more vertical orientation and their lifting has a pronounced effect on the anterior-posterior diameter of the chest.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 300.","responses":[{"text":"2 to 10","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"7 to 10","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2 to 6","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"7 to 12","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1 to 7","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12136,"text":"What is the term for the 8th to the 16th week of the respiratory system development stage?","explanation":"The development of the respiratory system is characterized by distinct stages that correspond to specific timeframes and developmental events. The **pseudoglandular stage** encompasses the period from the 8th to the 16th week of embryonic development. During this stage, the basic structural framework of the respiratory system begins to form. The conducting portion of the respiratory system, which includes the trachea, main bronchi, and segmental bronchi, is established. Furthermore, by the end of this stage, all major airway branches are formed, though the respiratory portion (responsible for gas exchange) remains undeveloped. It is termed \"pseudoglandular\" because the developing lung resembles exocrine glands in appearance during this stage, but the respiratory units capable of gas exchange, like alveoli, are not yet present.","reference":"Moore, Keith L., T. V. N. Persaud, and Mark G. Torchia. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 10th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier, 2016: 201.","responses":[{"text":"Terminal sac stage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alveolar stage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pseudoglandular stage","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Embryonic stage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Canalicular stage","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12632,"text":"During respiratory movements, ribs act as a lever. Which of the following is the fulcrum of this lever?","explanation":"During respiratory movements, the ribs function as levers, aiding in the expansion and contraction of the thoracic cavity. **Lateral to the tubercle of the rib** acts as the fulcrum of this lever system. \r\n\r\nThe tubercle of the rib articulates with the transverse process of the corresponding vertebra, forming the costotransverse joint. When the muscles of respiration contract, they cause the ribs to elevate or depress. The primary pivot point for this movement is lateral to the tubercle, allowing the rib to swing upwards and outwards, similar to the motion of a bucket handle. This movement effectively increases the transverse diameter of the thoracic cavity during inspiration.","reference":"Dow Lecture Slides. Respiratory Module-I, Subject: Anatomy; Topic: Thoracic movement with respiration; Sub-topic: Anteroposterior diameter.","responses":[{"text":"The tubercle of rib","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"At the angle of the rib","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"At the head of the rib","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial to the tubercle of rib","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral to the tubercle of rib","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12633,"text":"Which of the following muscles is not involved in forced inspiration?","explanation":"The **Erector spinae** is not involved in forced inspiration.\r\n\r\nForced inspiration requires the elevation of the ribcage and sternum to increase thoracic volume. This action recruits specific accessory muscles of respiration. The scalenus anterior, scalenus medius, and serratus anterior are primary muscles that assist in elevating the upper ribs. The serratus anterior also plays a role in elevating the ribs, especially when the arm is fixed, like during deep inspiration or during certain physical activities.\r\n\r\nThe erector spinae is a group of muscles and tendons that run vertically along the length of the spine on the back. While they play a vital role in extending the vertebral column and maintaining an upright posture, they do not directly contribute to the respiratory mechanism of forced inspiration.","reference":"(1) Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 491\r\n(2) Jeno SH, Varacallo M. Anatomy, back, latissimus dorsi. StatPearls. Published 2022. Accessed December 10, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK448120/","responses":[{"text":"Erector spinae","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Scalenus medius","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Scalenus anterior","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Latissimus dorsi","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serratus anterior","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12661,"text":"Which of the following structures is involved in the formation of the central tendon of the diaphragm?","explanation":"The **septum transversum** is involved in the formation of the central tendon of the diaphragm.\r\n\r\nDuring embryonic development, the diaphragm is formed from several components that migrate and fuse together. The septum transversum, which originates as a thick mass of cranial mesenchyme, migrates caudally and eventually contributes to the central tendon of the diaphragm. This central tendon is the aponeurotic center of the diaphragm to which the muscular fibers attach. The other structures mentioned, like thoracic somites, pleuroperitoneal membranes, mesentery of the esophagus, and cervical somites, also play roles in the formation and positioning of the diaphragm but not directly in the formation of the central tendon.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 11th ed. Saunders/Elsevier; 2020: 147.","responses":[{"text":"Cervical somites","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mesentery of the esophagus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pleuroperitoneal membranes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thoracic somites","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Septum transversum","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12662,"text":"Which of the following statements regarding the pleura is correct?","explanation":"The correct statement regarding the pleura is that **it forms the pulmonary ligament**.\r\n\r\nThe pleura is a serous membrane that covers the lungs and lines the thoracic cavity. It is divided into two layers: the visceral pleura, which is closely adherent to the lung, and the parietal pleura, which lines the thoracic wall, mediastinum, and diaphragm. The two layers are continuous with each other at the hilum of the lung. The pulmonary ligament is a double fold of pleura that extends inferiorly from the hilum and root of the lung. It provides some slack for the movements of the lung during respiration. \r\n\r\nThe pleura is sensitive (especially the parietal layer), it does not have respiratory epithelium (it has mesothelial cells), and while the two layers are closely associated, they can move against each other with the lubrication of a thin layer of serous fluid.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 327-330, 339.","responses":[{"text":"It has two layers tightly adherent to each other","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It forms the pulmonary ligament","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It is lined by respiratory epithelium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The sternal line of pleural reflection is similar on right and left sides","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is insensitive","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12663,"text":"The inferior vena cava passes through the diaphragm at which of the following spinal levels?","explanation":"The **inferior vena cava (IVC)** passes through the diaphragm at the spinal level **T8**.\r\n\r\nThe diaphragm is the primary muscle of respiration and it separates the thoracic and abdominal cavities. It has several apertures that allow structures to pass between the thorax and the abdomen. The IVC passes through the caval opening in the central tendon of the diaphragm, and this occurs at the T8 vertebral level. The opening for the IVC is the highest of the major apertures, reflecting the early return of the IVC to the heart relative to the other major structures that pass through the diaphragm.","reference":"(1) Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 163. (2) Shahid Z, Burns B. Anatomy, abdomen and pelvis, diaphragm. StatPearls. Published 2022. Accessed November 24, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470191/","responses":[{"text":"T8","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"C7","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"L1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"T12","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"T10","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12664,"text":"Which of the following structures passes through the diaphragm with the esophagus?","explanation":"The structure that passes through the diaphragm with the esophagus is the **Right vagus nerve**.\r\n\r\nThe diaphragm has three major openings: the caval opening (for the inferior vena cava), the esophageal hiatus (for the esophagus and the vagal trunks), and the aortic hiatus (for the aorta, thoracic duct, and azygos vein). The esophageal hiatus is situated in the right crus of the diaphragm at the level of the T10 vertebra. The right vagus nerve (posterior vagal trunk) and the left vagus nerve (anterior vagal trunk) pass through this hiatus alongside the esophagus. The right vagus nerve typically gives off branches around the esophagus and contributes to the formation of the esophageal plexus.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 536.","responses":[{"text":"Phrenic nerves","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sympathetic trunk","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thoracic duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Azygos vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right vagus nerve","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13061,"text":"Intercostal vessels and nerve run between which of the following thoracic intercostal muscles?","explanation":"The intercostal vessels and nerve run between the **internal and innermost intercostal muscles**.\r\n\r\nIn the thoracic intercostal spaces, three main muscle layers are present: the external intercostal, internal intercostal, and the innermost intercostal muscles. The neurovascular bundle, comprising the intercostal nerve and vessels (intercostal artery and vein), is located in the costal groove of the ribs, between the internal and innermost intercostal muscles. This position helps protect these structures from injury. Specifically, the bundle lies in the subcostal groove, running just inferior to the corresponding rib. When performing procedures like thoracocentesis (pleural fluid aspiration), care must be taken to avoid damaging this neurovascular bundle by placing the needle just above the rib.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 155.","responses":[{"text":"Subcostal and transversus thoracic muscles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Internal and innermost intercostal muscles","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"External and internal intercostal muscles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Innermost intercostal and transversus thoracic muscles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Innermost intercostal and subcostal muscles","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13070,"text":"A 42-year-old woman presents to the outpatient department with complaints of pain in the medial side of the forearm and wasting of hand muscles. The consultant diagnoses a compression of the lower trunk of the brachial plexus. Which of the following causes compression of the lower trunk of the brachial plexus?","explanation":"A **cervical rib** is an extra rib that arises from the seventh cervical vertebra. It's a congenital anomaly. The presence of a cervical rib can lead to compression of the lower trunk of the brachial plexus and the subclavian artery, leading to a set of symptoms known as \"thoracic outlet syndrome.\" The lower trunk of the brachial plexus primarily supplies the medial side of the forearm and intrinsic hand muscles. Therefore, its compression by the cervical rib leads to symptoms as described in the patient.","reference":"(1) Drake, Richard L. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Philadelphia, MO: Elsevier, 2020: 151.\r\n\r\n(2) Dahlin LB, Backman C, Düppe H, et al. Compression of the lower trunk of the brachial plexus by a cervical rib in two adolescent girls: case reports and surgical treatment. Journal of Brachial Plexus and Peripheral Nerve Injury. Published September 6, 2009. Accessed December 9, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2742518/","responses":[{"text":"Second rib fracture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cervical rib","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Abdominal rib","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"First rib fracture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Extra vertebrae","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13071,"text":"A 35-year-old man presents to the outpatient department with a complaint of chest pain that was felt in the ribs. After examination and investigation, a diagnosis of pressure on the intercostal nerves was made which resulted in a spasm of intercostal muscles. Which of the following muscles is unaffected?","explanation":"The muscle that is unaffected by pressure on the intercostal nerves among the options given is **Pectoralis major**.\r\n\r\nThe pectoralis major is a large muscle of the anterior chest wall and is primarily involved in the movements of the shoulder joint. It is innervated by the medial and lateral pectoral nerves, which are branches from the brachial plexus, and not by the intercostal nerves.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, the external intercostal, innermost intercostal, subcostal, and internal intercostal muscles are all innervated by the intercostal nerves. These muscles are found between the ribs and assist in the process of respiration. Any pressure or irritation to the intercostal nerves could result in pain and spasm of these muscles, but not of the pectoralis major.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 306.","responses":[{"text":"Pectoralis major","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Internal intercostal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Innermost intercostal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Subcostal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"External intercostal","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13072,"text":"Which of the following maintains the patency of the trachea?","explanation":"**Cartilaginous rings** are responsible for maintaining the patency of the trachea.\r\n\r\nThe trachea, commonly known as the windpipe, extends from the larynx to the bronchi and is a vital part of the respiratory system. To ensure that it remains open, especially during breathing, the anterior and lateral walls of the trachea have C-shaped rings made of hyaline cartilage. These cartilaginous rings prevent the trachea from collapsing, especially during inhalation when the intratracheal pressure might decrease. The open part of the 'C' shape is posterior, allowing for the esophagus to expand during swallowing. If these rings were not present, the trachea could potentially collapse during inspiration, hindering airflow to and from the lungs.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 1039.","responses":[{"text":"Surface tension of water","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Surfactant","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Air pressure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pseudostratified ciliated epithelium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cartilaginous rings","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13133,"text":"Which of the following thoracic joints is incorrectly paired with its classification?","explanation":"**Interchondral joints ---\u003e Secondary cartilaginous joints** is the incorrect pairing.\r\n\r\nInterchondral joints are found between the costal cartilages of the sixth and seventh, seventh and eighth, and eighth and ninth ribs. These are synovial plane joints, not secondary cartilaginous joints. Secondary cartilaginous joints, also known as symphyses, are characterized by a fibrocartilaginous disc between bones, which isn't the case for the interchondral joints. An example of a secondary cartilaginous joint in the thorax is the manubriosternal joint. \r\n\r\nIn summary:\r\n- **Interchondral joints** are synovial plane joints.\r\n- **Manubriosternal joint** is a secondary cartilaginous joint or symphysis.\r\n- **Second to seventh sternocostal joints** are synovial joints, except for the first, which is a primary cartilaginous joint.\r\n- **Xiphisternal joint** and **Costochondral joints** are primary cartilaginous joints.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 299.","responses":[{"text":"Second to seventh sternocostal joints ---\u003e Synovial joints","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interchondral joints ---\u003e Secondary cartilaginous joints","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Costochondral joints ---\u003e Primary cartilaginous joints","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Xiphisternal joint ---\u003e Primary cartilaginous joint","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Manubriosternal joint ---\u003e Secondary cartilaginous joint","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13135,"text":"Which of the following parts of the parietal pleura is supplied by the phrenic nerve?","explanation":"The **mediastinal pleura** is the part of the parietal pleura that lines the mediastinum. It is supplied by the phrenic nerve. The parietal pleura adheres closely to the thoracic wall, mediastinum, diaphragm, and pericardium. Different parts of the parietal pleura receive their nerve supply from distinct sources. The mediastinal pleura's innervation by the phrenic nerve means that conditions affecting the mediastinal pleura, like infections or inflammation, can lead to referred pain sensed over areas where the phrenic nerve provides sensory innervation. Specifically, irritation or conditions involving the mediastinal pleura might lead to referred pain in areas corresponding to the C3-C5 dermatomes, such as the shoulder tip, due to the origins of the phrenic nerve from these cervical spinal levels.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 339.","responses":[{"text":"Cervical part","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Visceral pleura","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Costal part","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diaphragmatic pleura (peripheral part)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mediastinal pleura","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13147,"text":"A newborn baby was observed to have continuous coughing and choking. There was an excessive amount of mucous and saliva secretion in the infant's mouth. The infant showed considerable difficulty breathing. The physician was not able to pass a catheter through the esophagus into the stomach. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"The described symptoms are indicative of **esophageal atresia and tracheoesophageal fistula**. In this congenital anomaly, the esophagus terminates prematurely as a blind pouch (esophageal atresia), and there is an abnormal connection (fistula) between the trachea and the esophagus. The inability to pass a catheter from the esophagus into the stomach confirms the presence of a blockage or atresia. The continuous coughing, choking, and breathing difficulties arise due to the entry of secretions and/or feedings from the esophagus into the trachea through the fistula, which can subsequently reach the lungs and cause aspiration. This is a medical emergency as it poses a risk of aspiration pneumonia. The excessive mucous and saliva in the mouth are due to the inability of secretions to pass into the stomach because of the esophageal atresia.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 750.","responses":[{"text":"Tracheal stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tracheal atresia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Esophageal atresia and tracheoesophageal fistula","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyaline membrane disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Duodenal atresia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13149,"text":"Which of the following limits the duration of inspiration and subsequently increases the inspiratory rate?","explanation":"The **pneumotaxic center**, located in the pons of the brainstem, plays a critical role in regulating the rate and pattern of breathing. Specifically, the pneumotaxic center influences the duration of inspiration. When this center sends more frequent signals, it inhibits the activity of the dorsal respiratory group of neurons, leading to a shorter duration of the inspiratory phase. As a consequence, inspiration ends prematurely, and the inspiratory rate increases. Conversely, when the activity of the pneumotaxic center decreases, inspiration lasts longer, leading to a decrease in the inspiratory rate. Hence, by adjusting its output, the pneumotaxic center can fine-tune the rhythm of breathing to match the body's needs.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 532.","responses":[{"text":"Dorsal respiratory group of neurons","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chemotaxic center","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Apneustic center","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pneumotaxic center","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventral respiratory group of neurons","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13153,"text":"Which of the following has a significant direct stimulatory effect on central chemoreceptors?","explanation":"The central chemoreceptors, located near the medulla of the brain, are primarily sensitive to changes in the pH of cerebrospinal fluid (CSF). These changes in pH are predominantly caused by alterations in the carbon dioxide (CO₂) levels in the blood. When arterial blood CO₂ levels rise, CO₂ easily crosses the blood-brain barrier and dissolves in the CSF. Inside the CSF, CO₂ combines with water (H₂O) to form carbonic acid (H₂CO₃), which subsequently dissociates into bicarbonate (HCO₃⁻) and hydrogen ions (H⁺). Therefore, it's the **increased hydrogen ions in cerebrospinal fluid** that directly stimulate the central chemoreceptors, leading to an increase in the rate and depth of breathing to eliminate the excess CO₂ and bring the system back to equilibrium.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 533.","responses":[{"text":"Increased pH of blood","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased hydrogen ions in cerebrospinal fluid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreases oxygen partial pressure of blood","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased carbon dioxide in cerebrospinal fluid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased carbon dioxide in blood","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13158,"text":"Mountain climbers have found that when they ascend a mountain slowly, over a longer period of days rather than a period of hours, they breathe much more deeply and therefore can withstand far lower atmospheric oxygen concentrations than when they ascend rapidly. What is this phenomenon called?","explanation":"The phenomenon in which the body undergoes physiological adjustments in response to changes in the environment, such as low oxygen levels at high altitudes, is called **acclimatization**. When mountain climbers ascend gradually, their bodies have time to adapt to the reduced oxygen levels. This adaptation involves increased depth of breathing, elevated production of red blood cells, and enhanced capacity of the tissues to utilize oxygen, allowing them to function more efficiently in low-oxygen conditions. Acclimatization is beneficial as it reduces the risk of altitude sickness, which can occur when there's a rapid ascent to high altitudes without giving the body adequate time to adjust.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 536.","responses":[{"text":"Modification","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acclimatization","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Alteration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Accommodation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Familiarization","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13159,"text":"Which of the following is the most powerful respiratory stimulus for breathing in healthy individuals?","explanation":"The primary driver for breathing in healthy individuals is the concentration of carbon dioxide in the blood. When carbon dioxide levels rise, the blood becomes more acidic (decreased pH), which stimulates the respiratory centers in the brain to increase the rate and depth of breathing. This helps to expel the excess carbon dioxide from the body and return the pH to its normal range. Although oxygen levels can also influence respiratory drive, under normal circumstances, it is not the primary stimulus. Thus, in healthy individuals, an **increased carbon dioxide in blood** serves as the most powerful respiratory stimulus for breathing.","reference":"(1) Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 533. (2) Brinkman JE, Toro F, Sharma S. Physiology, respiratory drive. StatPearls. Published 2022. Accessed December 8, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482414/","responses":[{"text":"Loss of oxygen in tissue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"High pH and high carbon dioxide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increase in pH of blood","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decrease in pH of blood","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased carbon dioxide in blood","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13160,"text":"A patient presents to the emergency room with rib fractures. His breathing is painful so he is taking rapid, and shallow breaths. His respiratory rate is 40 breaths per minute and his tidal volume is 200 ml. What would be his minute respiratory volume?","explanation":"The minute respiratory volume (or minute ventilation) is calculated as the product of the respiratory rate and the tidal volume. It represents the total volume of air inspired or expired per minute.\r\n\r\nGiven:\r\n- Respiratory rate = 40 breaths/minute\r\n- Tidal volume = 200 ml/breath\r\n\r\nMinute respiratory volume = Respiratory rate × Tidal volume  \r\n= 40 breaths/minute × 200 ml/breath  \r\n= 8000 ml/minute\r\n\r\nThus, the correct answer is **8000 ml/minute**.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 497.","responses":[{"text":"4600 ml/minute","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2000 ml/minute","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"400 ml/minute","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"200 ml/minute","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"8000 ml/minute","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13161,"text":"A 32-year-old man presents to the emergency room with a complaint of having trouble breathing after he met a road traffic accident. His lung function test shows his functional residual capacity to be reduced. What does this capacity indicate?","explanation":"**Functional Residual Capacity (FRC)** represents the volume of **air remaining in the lungs after a normal exhalation** (or tidal expiration). Specifically, FRC is the sum of the Expiratory Reserve Volume (ERV) and the Residual Volume (RV). The significance of FRC is that it maintains alveolar oxygenation between breaths and prevents drastic fluctuations in blood gases during the respiratory cycle.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 495.","responses":[{"text":"The amount of air remaining in the lungs after normal expiration","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"The amount of air remaining in the lungs after maximum expiration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Combination of inspiratory reserve volume and tidal volume","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The amount of air expelled out after each normal expiration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The amount of air inspired and expired during each normal breath","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13162,"text":"Which of the following pressure differences is responsible for distention of the lungs?","explanation":"**Transpulmonary pressure** is the difference between the alveolar pressure and the intrapleural (or pleural) pressure. It determines the force that's applied on the lungs to expand or distend them. Specifically, the transpulmonary pressure keeps the lungs inflated. When this pressure increases, the lungs expand, and when it decreases, the lungs recoil.","reference":"(1) Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 492, 493.","responses":[{"text":"Airway opening pressure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alveolar pressure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transpulmonary pressure","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Transthoracic pressure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Airway closing pressure","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13163,"text":"Gases such as oxygen and carbon dioxide cross the respiratory membrane by which of the following methods?","explanation":"The movement of these gases across the respiratory membrane is primarily due to **simple passive diffusion**. Oxygen diffuses from the alveoli, where its concentration is high, into the blood, where its concentration is lower. Conversely, carbon dioxide diffuses from the blood, where its concentration is higher, into the alveoli, where its concentration is lower. This process doesn't require any energy or specific transport proteins. The lipid solubility of the gases and the thinness of the respiratory membrane facilitate this diffusion.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 511.","responses":[{"text":"Passive diffusion through the lipid bilayer","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Facilitated diffusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secondary active transport","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Specific gas transport proteins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primary active transport","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13164,"text":"Which of the following events occurs in the lungs, when the partial pressure of oxygen falls below 73 mmHg in the alveolar air?","explanation":"When the partial pressure of oxygen (pO₂) in the alveolar air falls below a certain threshold, typically around 73 mmHg, the lungs exhibit a unique physiologic response known as hypoxic pulmonary vasoconstriction (HPV).\r\n\r\nHPV is a homeostatic mechanism that diverts blood away from poorly ventilated lung regions with low oxygen levels to better-ventilated regions with higher oxygen levels. This action optimizes oxygenation of the blood.\r\n\r\n**Constriction of blood vessels adjacent to alveoli**: In regions of the lung where alveolar oxygen is low, the small pulmonary arteries constrict. This reduces blood flow to the hypoxic areas, ensuring that the majority of the blood flows through areas of the lung that have a higher oxygen content.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 505.","responses":[{"text":"Damage to type I pneumocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased physiological shunt","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increase in nitrogen content","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Expansion of alveoli","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Constriction of blood vessel adjacent to alveoli","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13165,"text":"A 24-year-old man presents to the outpatient department with complaints of a runny nose; red, itchy, and watery eyes; sneezing, and cough related to post-nasal drip. A diagnosis of allergic rhinitis is made. Which of the following chemical mediators is involved?","explanation":"Allergic rhinitis is an inflammatory response to allergens such as pollen, dust mites, or pet dander. When an individual is exposed to an allergen, it triggers a hypersensitive reaction leading to the release of various chemical mediators from mast cells and basophils.\r\n\r\n**Histamine** is a primary chemical mediator released in response to allergen exposure. Once released, histamine binds to its receptors, leading to increased vascular permeability, which results in the classic symptoms of allergic reactions: redness, itching, swelling, and watery secretions. This is the reason antihistamines (e.g., diphenhydramine) are commonly used to treat allergic rhinitis—they block the histamine receptors and prevent or reduce the symptoms.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 287.","responses":[{"text":"Glycine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ranitidine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Histamine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Glutamate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diphenhydramine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13166,"text":"A person admitted to the hospital is in a coma. Analysis of arterial blood gave the following values: pCO₂ 56 mmHg, HCO₃ 25 mmol/l, and pH 7.1. What is the underlying acid-base disorder?","explanation":"Given the arterial blood gas values:\r\n- **pCO₂**: 56 mmHg (Normal: 35-45 mmHg)\r\n- **HCO₃** (bicarbonate): 25 mmol/l (Normal: 22-28 mmol/l)\r\n- **pH**: 7.1 (Normal: 7.35-7.45)\r\n\r\nThe elevated pCO₂ indicates an accumulation of carbon dioxide, which acidifies the blood. The HCO₃ level is within the normal range, and the pH value of 7.1 is lower than the normal range, indicating an acidic state.\r\n\r\nGiven these results:\r\n1. Elevated pCO₂ indicates a respiratory component.\r\n2. The pH is decreased, suggesting acidosis.\r\n3. The bicarbonate level (HCO₃) is normal, indicating that the metabolic component has not compensated for the respiratory component.\r\n\r\nFrom the above data, the most appropriate diagnosis is **Respiratory Acidosis**.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 416.","responses":[{"text":"Pulmonary edema","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metabolic acidosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metabolic alkalosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Respiratory alkalosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Respiratory acidosis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13167,"text":"A 4-year-old boy presents to the emergency room with complaints of malaise, lethargy, tachypnea, sore throat, abdominal pain, vomiting, and dehydration for the past week. He was known to have type I diabetes mellitus. His vitals showed a heart rate of 156 beats per minute, blood pressure of 90/55 mmHg, plasma glucose of 428.4 mg/dL, pH 6.7, pO₂ 5.2kPa, pCO₂ 4.4 kPa. The patient is diagnosed with Acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS). Dipalmityl phosphatidylcholine is the main constituent of pulmonary surfactants, 45% of which comes from de novo biosynthesis. Which of the following molecules give rise to the de novo synthesis of phosphatidylcholine in the lungs?","explanation":"Dipalmitoyl phosphatidylcholine (DPPC) is a primary component of pulmonary surfactant, crucial for reducing surface tension in the alveoli. Its synthesis is of significant importance for lung function.\r\n\r\nThe de novo synthesis of phosphatidylcholine involves the CDP-choline pathway. In this pathway:\r\n\r\n1. Choline is activated by phosphorylation to produce phosphocholine.\r\n2. Phosphocholine then reacts with cytidine triphosphate (CTP) to produce **cytidine diphosphate choline (CDP-choline)**.\r\n3. CDP-choline then reacts with diacylglycerol to produce phosphatidylcholine.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 203.","responses":[{"text":"Cytidine diacylglycerol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cytidine triphosphate choline","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cytidine diphosphate choline","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cytidine phosphate choline","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lysophosphatidylcholine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13168,"text":"A person admitted to the hospital is in a coma. Analysis of arterial blood gave the following values: pCO₂ 16.1 mmHg, HCO₃ 5 mmol/l, and pH 7.1. What is the underlying acid-base disorder?","explanation":"Given the patient's arterial blood values:\r\n- pCO₂ is decreased (Normal: 35-45 mmHg)\r\n- HCO₃⁻ is decreased (Normal: 22-28 mmol/l)\r\n- pH is decreased (Normal: 7.35-7.45)\r\n\r\nLet's break down the results:\r\n\r\n1. The **low pH** indicates acidemia.\r\n2. The **decreased pCO₂** suggests a respiratory component is working to counteract this acidemia, pointing toward a compensatory mechanism.\r\n3. The **decreased HCO₃⁻** confirms a primary metabolic component.\r\n\r\nBased on these findings, the underlying acid-base disorder is **Metabolic Acidosis**. Additionally, the low pCO₂ indicates a respiratory compensation (as the lungs try to blow off CO₂ to raise the pH). However, despite the compensatory mechanism, the pH is still below normal, indicating the compensation is not complete.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 416.","responses":[{"text":"Metabolic acidosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Respiratory acidosis with partial compensation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Respiratory acidosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Respiratory alkalosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metabolic alkalosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13169,"text":"Which of the following is the least likely characteristic of asthma?","explanation":"Asthma is a chronic inflammatory disorder of the airways characterized by bronchial hyperreactivity and variable, recurring episodes of airflow obstruction. The pathogenesis involves multiple cells, including mast cells, eosinophils, and T lymphocytes. \r\n\r\n- **Mast cell activation and degranulation**: Mast cells play a pivotal role in asthma, releasing mediators like histamine which cause bronchoconstriction.\r\n  \r\n- **Airway hyperresponsiveness**: A hallmark of asthma, leading to bronchoconstriction in response to various stimuli.\r\n  \r\n- **Increased mucus production**: Mucus hypersecretion contributes to airflow obstruction.\r\n  \r\n- **Infiltration of eosinophils into the airways**: Eosinophilic inflammation is a central feature in asthma.\r\n\r\nHowever, **increased IgG immunoglobulins** are not typically associated with asthma. Instead, elevated levels of IgE antibodies, linked with allergen exposure and eosinophil activation, are a characteristic feature.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 683, 684.","responses":[{"text":"Airway hyperresponsiveness","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased IgG immunoglobulins","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mast cell activation and degranulation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased mucus production","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Infiltration of eosinophils into the airways","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13170,"text":"Why do patients with emphysema often exhibit pursed-lip breathing?","explanation":"This is primarily **to increase airway pressure during expiration**, which helps in keeping the airways open longer, thereby **reducing air trapping**. Emphysema is characterized by the destruction of alveolar walls and a loss of elastic recoil in the lungs. This causes airway collapse during expiration. By exhaling through pursed lips, patients can create a back-pressure in the airways, preventing premature collapse of the smaller bronchioles. This helps in better emptying of the lungs during exhalation and reduces hyperinflation. Consequently, it also improves oxygen and carbon dioxide exchange. Pursed-lip breathing is a learned technique for many with chronic obstructive pulmonary diseases, such as emphysema, and is used to relieve symptoms and improve ventilation.","reference":"Nguyen JD, Duong H. Pursed-lip Breathing. StatPearls. Published 2022. Accessed December 8, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK545289/","responses":[{"text":"To prevent cyanosis and hypoperfusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"To regulate filling of lungs that have increased compliance","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"To avoid chest discomfort during inspiration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"To increase airway pressure during expiration to reduce air trapping","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Reflex response to severe breathlessness","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13171,"text":"Which of the following is the most common congenital disease affecting the lungs?","explanation":"**Congenital Diaphragmatic Hernia (CDH)** is the most common congenital disease affecting the lungs.\r\n\r\nCongenital diaphragmatic hernia arises from a defect in the diaphragm, allowing abdominal organs, typically the intestine, liver, or stomach, to migrate into the thoracic cavity. This intrusion hampers proper lung development and can lead to pulmonary hypoplasia, or underdevelopment of the lungs. Infants with CDH often present with respiratory distress shortly after birth due to reduced lung volume and function. The most common type of CDH is the Bochdalek hernia, occurring postero-laterally. CDH poses significant challenges because both the herniated organs and the underdeveloped lungs need management. Early diagnosis, often prenatally with ultrasound, and postnatal surgical correction are crucial for survival.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 674.","responses":[{"text":"Lack of pulmonary surfactant protein B","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pleural effusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tracheoesophageal fistula","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Marfan syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Congenital diaphragmatic hernia","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13172,"text":"Which of the following statements is most appropriate about lung diseases?","explanation":"The most appropriate statement about lung diseases is: **Obstructive lung diseases are characterized by limitation to airflow**.\r\n\r\nObstructive lung diseases, such as asthma, chronic bronchitis, and emphysema, are characterized by a limitation to airflow due to partial or complete obstruction at any level, from the trachea down to the respiratory bronchioles. The hallmark of these diseases is reduced expiratory flow rate. In contrast, restrictive lung diseases, such as pulmonary fibrosis or sarcoidosis, are characterized by reduced expansion of the lungs, leading to decreased total lung capacity. Restrictive lung diseases do not typically involve obstruction of the airways. Instead, the problem is with the expansion of the lung or chest wall, making it difficult to fill the lungs with air.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 678.","responses":[{"text":"Restrictive lung diseases are characterized by reduced expiratory flow rate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Restrictive lung diseases are characterized by limitation to airflow","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obstructive lung diseases are characterized by limitation to airflow","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Restrictive lung diseases have partial obstruction at the level of bronchi","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obstructive lung diseases are characterized by reduced expansion of lungs","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13173,"text":"Concerning community-acquired pneumonia which of the following statements is the most appropriate?","explanation":"The most appropriate statement concerning community-acquired pneumonia (CAP) is: **Risk factors include age (\u003c5, \u003e65 years)**.\r\n\r\nCommunity-acquired pneumonia (CAP) refers to pneumonia (an infection of the lungs) acquired outside of healthcare settings. Among the risk factors for CAP, age is significant, with the very young (\u003c5 years) and the elderly (\u003e65 years) being particularly susceptible due to either immature or waning immunity. While various organisms can cause CAP, the most common is *Streptococcus pneumoniae*, a gram-positive bacterium. The symptoms of CAP can vary, but they do not always include pleurisy or hemoptysis. Notably, the incidence of CAP is influenced by various factors like age, comorbidities, and geography, but stating a specific rate without context might be oversimplifying.","reference":"(1) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 709. \r\n(2) Regunath H, Oba Y. Community-acquired pneumonia. StatPearls. Published 2022. Accessed December 8, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430749/","responses":[{"text":"The incidence is 5-11 cases per 10,000 population","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The most frequently identified organisms are gram negative bacteria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Symptoms always include pleurisy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Risk factors include age (\u003c5, \u003e65 years)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Symptoms always include hemoptysis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13174,"text":"A 75-year-old man, hospitalized for the past week with COVID-19 pneumonia, develops a sudden onset of tachypnea and dyspnea. His lips appear blue and his oxygen saturation drops drastically. Chest X-Ray shows diffuse bilateral infiltrates (\"white lungs\"). What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"The most likely diagnosis for this patient is **Acute Respiratory Distress Syndrome (ARDS)**.\r\n\r\nARDS is a form of acute diffuse lung injury that is associated with a variety of etiologies, including infections (like COVID-19), trauma, and sepsis. It is characterized clinically by rapid onset of severe dyspnea, hypoxemia (as evidenced by blue lips and decreased oxygen saturation in this patient), and diffuse pulmonary infiltrates on chest imaging, often described as \"white lungs\" on X-ray due to bilateral alveolar filling. The hallmark of ARDS is diffuse damage to the alveolar-capillary interface, leading to increased permeability, pulmonary edema, and reduced lung compliance.\r\n\r\nGiven the patient's recent history of COVID-19 pneumonia, the sudden deterioration with respiratory symptoms, and the characteristic chest X-ray findings, **Acute Respiratory Distress Syndrome** is the most probable diagnosis.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 672, 673, 710.","responses":[{"text":"Acute chronic bronchitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute respiratory distress syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Miliary tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Septicemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fat embolism","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13175,"text":"A 59-year-old man presents to the outpatient department with a complaint of frequent episodes of shortness of breath along with occasional cough with minimum sputum production for the last four years. He has been a known smoker for ten years. On chest auscultation, respiratory wheezes are heard. Chest X-Ray shows hyperinflation of both lungs. Pulmonary function tests show a decreased FEV₁/FVC ratio. Which of the following conditions is most likely to be a cause of these findings?","explanation":"**Emphysema** is the most likely cause of the described findings in the patient.\r\n\r\nEmphysema is a type of Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease (COPD) characterized by permanent enlargement of the airspaces distal to the terminal bronchioles accompanied by the destruction of their walls, without obvious fibrosis. Common risk factors include smoking, as in this patient. Symptoms typically include progressive dyspnea and minimal sputum production. On examination, the chest might appear hyperinflated (\"barrel chest\"), and respiratory wheezes may be heard on auscultation. Chest X-Ray can show hyperinflation of the lungs, while the hallmark finding on Pulmonary Function Tests (PFTs) is a decreased FEV₁/FVC ratio, indicating an obstructive pattern. \r\n\r\nGiven the patient's history of smoking, clinical presentation, and diagnostic findings, **emphysema** is the most consistent diagnosis.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 681, 682.","responses":[{"text":"Sarcoidosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic pulmonary embolism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Emphysema","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Diffuse alveolar damage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Restrictive lung disease","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13176,"text":"Which of the following is the most helpful and preferred method of establishing the diagnosis of asthma?","explanation":"**Spirometry** is the most helpful and preferred method for establishing the diagnosis of asthma.\r\n\r\nAsthma is a chronic inflammatory disorder of the airways that leads to recurrent episodes of wheezing, breathlessness, and coughing. Spirometry provides an objective measurement of lung function and is pivotal for both the diagnosis and management of asthma. It measures the volume and flow of air during inhalation and exhalation. One of the hallmark findings in asthma is a reversible airflow obstruction, which is demonstrated by a significant increase in the Forced Expiratory Volume in the first second (FEV₁) after the administration of a bronchodilator.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 682.","responses":[{"text":"Arterial blood gases","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chest X-Ray","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulse oximeter","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chest computerized tomography (CT) scan","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spirometry","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13177,"text":"Which of the following is the single most effective test used in the DOTS strategy for the diagnosis of infective tuberculosis?","explanation":"The **Directly Observed Treatment, Short-course (DOTS)** strategy is an internationally recognized approach for TB control. Among the diagnostic tools available for detecting pulmonary tuberculosis (TB), the **Sputum AFB smear microscopy** stands out as the primary and most effective test, especially within the DOTS framework.\r\n\r\nSputum AFB smear microscopy is a rapid, cost-effective method that detects acid-fast bacilli (AFB) in sputum samples, which are characteristic of Mycobacterium tuberculosis, the causative agent of TB. While other tests like the Gene Xpert and chest X-ray provide valuable insights, and the Gene Xpert, in particular, offers rapid molecular detection of TB with resistance patterns, the AFB smear remains the cornerstone in resource-limited settings due to its accessibility and affordability.","reference":"Dow Lecture Slides. Respiratory-I Module; Subject: Community Medicine; Topic: Tuberculosis; Sub-Topic: TB investigations/diagnosis.","responses":[{"text":"Chest X-Ray","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tuberculin test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sputum AFB smear microscopy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Gene Xpert test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sputum for alpha fetoprotein (AFP) culture","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13178,"text":"A 30-year-old woman is admitted to the medical ward with a complaint of acute exacerbation of bronchial asthma- a disease that she has been suffering from for six years. She has been advised of certain pulmonary function tests. Which of the following results are expected?","explanation":"Bronchial asthma is a type of **obstructive lung disease** characterized by bronchoconstriction, inflammation, and mucus production that can lead to airway narrowing. Pulmonary function tests (PFTs) are a valuable tool in assessing lung function in patients with asthma.\r\n\r\nIn asthma and other obstructive lung diseases, there's a marked reduction in the forced expiratory volume in one second (FEV₁) compared to the forced vital capacity (FVC). This is because the narrowed and inflamed airways impede the rapid outflow of air. As a result, the **FEV₁/FVC ratio is reduced** in patients with asthma, especially during an acute exacerbation. Additionally, the total amount of air forcibly expelled in one second, known as FEV₁, is also typically decreased in asthma due to the obstruction.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 89, 91.","responses":[{"text":"Pulmonary function tests are not indicated","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"FEV₁/FVC ratio is increased","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"FEV₁/FVC ratio is reduced","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"FEV₁/FVC ratio is normal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"FEV₁ will be increased","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13179,"text":"A 4-year-old boy was brought to the outpatient department with complaints of nasal blockage and purulent discharge from the nose for four days. He is suspected to have inhaled a foreign body in the right main bronchus. Which anatomic feature of the right main bronchus favors the entry of a foreign body into it rather than the left main bronchus?","explanation":"The trachea bifurcates into the left and right main bronchi, which lead to the lungs. The **right main bronchus is wider, shorter, and more vertically oriented** compared to the left main bronchus. Due to its vertical orientation, the right main bronchus is more aligned with the trachea. This anatomical alignment facilitates the direct descent of aspirated foreign bodies into the right main bronchus, especially in children, more frequently than into the left main bronchus. Hence, in cases of foreign body aspiration, it is more common for the foreign body to lodge in the right bronchus due to its direct continuation with the trachea. This makes the statement that the **\"Right main bronchus is more aligned with the trachea\"** the correct anatomic feature that favors the entry of a foreign body into the right main bronchus.","reference":"(1) Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 173. (2) Kumar S, Al-Abri R, Sharma A, Al-Kindi H, Mishra P. Management of pediatric tracheobronchial foreign body aspiration. Oman Medical Journal. Published October 2010. Accessed December 8, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5556322/","responses":[{"text":"Right main bronchus passes anterior to esophagus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right main bronchus is more aligned with the trachea","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Right main bronchus is longer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right main bronchus is narrower","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right main bronchus is horizontal","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13180,"text":"A 40-year-old woman presents to the outpatient department with complaints of chronic cough, shortness of breath, and cyanosis. She is diagnosed with restrictive lung disease on a pulmonary function test. Which of the following findings of the pulmonary function test suggest the diagnosis of restrictive lung disease?","explanation":"Restrictive lung diseases are characterized by a reduction in lung volume, resulting in a decreased ability for lung expansion and a reduced forced vital capacity (FVC). In restrictive lung disease, both the forced expiratory volume in the first second (FEV₁) and FVC are reduced. However, the reduction in FVC is typically more significant than the reduction in FEV₁. As a result, the ratio of FEV₁ to FVC (FEV₁/FVC ratio) is usually either normal or increased in patients with restrictive lung diseases. Thus, one of the hallmark findings in pulmonary function tests for restrictive lung disease is a **FEV₁/FVC ratio that is increased**. This differentiates restrictive lung diseases from obstructive lung diseases, where the FEV₁/FVC ratio is reduced due to a more pronounced decrease in FEV₁ compared to FVC.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 92.","responses":[{"text":"Decreased FEV₁","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"FEV₁/FVC ratio is increased","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased FVC","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"No change in FEV₁/FVC ratio","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"FEV₁/FVC ratio is reduced","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15545,"text":"During a session of pleural effusion drainage, the physician asked the trainee to keep the needle just above the upper border of the lower rib. This was done to avoid injury to which of the following?","explanation":"During pleural effusion drainage, the needle is inserted just above the upper border of the lower rib to avoid injury to the neurovascular bundle that runs along the costal groove of each rib. This bundle includes the **intercostal nerve**, **intercostal artery**, and **intercostal vein**. The specific arrangement within the costal groove, from top to bottom, is vein-artery-nerve (often remembered by the mnemonic 'VAN'). Inserting the needle above the rib avoids potential injury to these structures, especially the intercostal artery and nerve, which lie closest to the lower border of the rib. An injury to these structures can lead to significant bleeding and cause sharp, shooting pain along the thoracic wall. Therefore, to minimize complications, it is standard practice to target just above the upper border of the lower rib.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 152, 162.","responses":[{"text":"Long thoracic nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intercostal vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neurovascular bundle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intercostal nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Intercostal artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15562,"text":"Which ions move outside of the red blood cells in the chloride shift?","explanation":"The chloride shift, also known as the Hamburger shift, is a process that occurs in red blood cells (RBCs) to facilitate carbon dioxide transport from the tissues to the lungs for excretion. As carbon dioxide enters the RBCs, it reacts with water to form carbonic acid under the influence of the enzyme carbonic anhydrase. This carbonic acid then dissociates into bicarbonate ions (hydrogen carbonate ions) and hydrogen ions.\r\n\r\nThe **bicarbonate ions (hydrogen carbonate ions)** are the ones that predominantly move out of the RBCs into the plasma. To maintain electrical neutrality within the RBCs, as these negatively charged bicarbonate ions move out, **chloride ions** move into the RBCs from the plasma, hence the name \"chloride shift.\"","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 528.","responses":[{"text":"Sodium ions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chloride ions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcium ions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Potassium ions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydrogen carbonate ions","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15611,"text":"Which of the following parts of the respiratory tract has the maximum number of smooth muscles?","explanation":"The respiratory tract is structured to facilitate the movement of air to and from the alveoli, where gas exchange takes place. The amount of smooth muscle in the walls of the respiratory tract varies depending on the specific segment.\r\n\r\nAmong the options provided, the **bronchioles** have the maximum number of smooth muscles. In fact, smooth muscle is a defining feature of bronchioles. This musculature allows the bronchioles to adjust their diameter, playing a crucial role in regulating airflow and resistance within the lungs. The bronchioles lack cartilage, which is present in the trachea and bronchi to maintain their open structure. Hence, the bronchioles primarily rely on smooth muscles to modulate their caliber, especially during bronchoconstriction or bronchodilation.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, the trachea and bronchi contain cartilage rings or plates, respectively. Alveoli lack any significant muscle tissue, and respiratory bronchioles have fewer smooth muscles compared to bronchioles.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2018: 350.","responses":[{"text":"Bronchi","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alveoli","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bronchiole","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Respiratory bronchiole","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trachea","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15695,"text":"The lungs receive arterial blood supply from two sources: the pulmonary arteries and the bronchial arteries. From which of the following does the right bronchial artery originate?","explanation":"The lungs receive dual blood supply: the pulmonary arteries deliver deoxygenated blood for oxygenation, while the bronchial arteries supply oxygenated blood to the lung tissue itself. There are usually two left bronchial arteries and one right bronchial artery. The left bronchial arteries typically arise directly from the thoracic aorta. The **right bronchial artery** often originates from one of the nearby vessels rather than the thoracic aorta directly. Most commonly, it arises from a shared trunk with a posterior intercostal artery. Among the options given, the **third posterior intercostal artery** is the most likely source for the origin of the right bronchial artery.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 177.","responses":[{"text":"Third posterior intercostal artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior surface of the thoracic aorta","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Second intercostal artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Posterior surface of the thoracic aorta","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Upper left bronchial artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15696,"text":"A patient comes to the emergency department with a low-pitched, hoarse voice, and noisy breathing. On examination, left vocal cords are found to be affected. Damage to which nerve can result in these findings?","explanation":"The symptoms described – a hoarse voice and noisy breathing – are indicative of vocal cord paralysis or dysfunction. The **left recurrent laryngeal nerve** is responsible for the innervation of almost all the intrinsic muscles of the larynx. The recurrent laryngeal nerve is a branch of the vagus nerve (cranial nerve X) and it supplies motor function to the vocal cords, allowing them to move and produce sound. If the left recurrent laryngeal nerve is damaged, the left vocal cord would become paralyzed and would not move efficiently, leading to the symptoms described. Furthermore, the left recurrent laryngeal nerve takes a longer route, looping under the aortic arch, making it more vulnerable to injury or compression by aortic aneurysms or other thoracic pathologies.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 226.","responses":[{"text":"Vagus nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Internal laryngeal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left recurrent laryngeal","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Intercostal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"External laryngeal","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15697,"text":"A 12-year-old girl presents to the emergency department with chest pain and labored breathing after falling off her bicycle. A chest x-ray reveals a fracture of the first rib. Which one of the following arteries is associated with the affected rib?","explanation":"The first rib is anatomically positioned close to the **subclavian artery**. The subclavian artery passes over the superior surface of the first rib, lying posterior to the clavicle. Due to its proximity, a fracture of the first rib poses a potential risk of injury to the subclavian artery. Trauma to the first rib requires significant force because of its protective positioning beneath the clavicle and its robust structure. Thus, when a fracture of the first rib occurs, clinicians should be vigilant about possible vascular or neurological complications related to the structures nearby. The subclavian artery's injury can lead to complications like hematoma, pulsatile mass, or signs of distal ischemia.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 726.","responses":[{"text":"Internal thoracic artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intercostal arteries","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Perforating arteries","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carotid artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Subclavian artery","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15878,"text":"Which of the following pressures corresponds to the elastic forces which tend to collapse the lung?","explanation":"The pressure that corresponds to the elastic forces which tend to collapse the lung is the **transpulmonary pressure**. Transpulmonary pressure is the difference between the alveolar pressure and the pleural pressure. It represents the distending force across the lung wall. When the lung is at rest, especially at the end of a normal exhalation (end-expiratory level), the transpulmonary pressure is balanced by the elastic recoil of the lung. In essence, the elastic properties of the lung tissue and the surface tension within the alveoli work to collapse the lung, while the transpulmonary pressure counteracts these forces to keep the lung expanded. A positive transpulmonary pressure means that the inside of the alveoli has a higher pressure than the outside, ensuring that the lungs remain inflated.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 492.","responses":[{"text":"Pleural","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transpulmonary","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lung","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alveolar","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transthoracic","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15880,"text":"An organ that is present in children and regresses by puberty is a constituent of which of the following mediastinum?","explanation":"The organ referred to is the **thymus**, and it is located in the **superior mediastinum**. The thymus is a lymphoid organ and plays a crucial role in the development and maturation of T-lymphocytes (T-cells) during childhood. These T-cells are vital components of the adaptive immune system. As one ages, especially after puberty, the thymus gradually shrinks and is replaced by adipose tissue, a process termed involution. Although smaller in size and less active in adults, remnants of the thymus can often persist into old age.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 215-217.","responses":[{"text":"Middle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Posterior","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15881,"text":"Trachealis is a band of muscle that exists between the open ends of the tracheal cartilages. What is its type?","explanation":"The **trachealis** muscle is a type of **smooth muscle**. This muscle extends longitudinally along the posterior aspect of the trachea, connecting the open ends of the C-shaped tracheal cartilages. Its function is to allow the trachea to constrict slightly during processes such as coughing, helping to expel mucus or other obstructions. It also provides flexibility and support to the trachea, allowing it to change diameter in response to various physiological conditions. The smooth muscle nature of trachealis contrasts with skeletal muscle, which is under voluntary control and typically attaches to bones. Smooth muscles, such as the trachealis, are involuntary and are found in the walls of many internal organs and structures, allowing them to constrict and dilate as needed.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2018: 348.","responses":[{"text":"Hyaline","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Smooth","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Skeletal and smooth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Skeletal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cardiac","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15882,"text":"Which respiratory organ has both skeletal muscles and cartilage?","explanation":"The **larynx** is the respiratory organ that possesses both skeletal muscles and cartilage. The larynx, commonly known as the voice box, is an essential structure situated between the pharynx and the trachea. It plays a pivotal role in phonation, breathing, and preventing the aspiration of food into the trachea. Structurally, the larynx is made up of several cartilages, including the thyroid cartilage, cricoid cartilage, and arytenoid cartilages, among others. These cartilages provide rigidity and support. The skeletal muscles of the larynx, like the cricothyroid and the posterior cricoarytenoid muscles, are involved in the movement of the vocal cords and regulation of the size of the glottis, which in turn affects voice modulation and protects the airway. The coordinated action of these muscles and cartilages ensures the proper functioning of the larynx in respiration and speech.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2018: 350.","responses":[{"text":"Trachea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Terminal bronchiole","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Larynx","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Alveoli","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Respiratory bronchiole","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15885,"text":"In which of the following conditions is a barrel-shaped chest observed on examination?","explanation":"A barrel-shaped chest is typically observed in patients with **emphysema**. Emphysema is characterized by the permanent enlargement of air spaces distal to the terminal bronchioles, along with destruction of the alveolar walls without evident fibrosis. This leads to a loss of lung elasticity and a resultant increase in lung volume. The increased anterior-posterior diameter of the thorax, commonly referred to as a \"barrel chest,\" is a compensatory mechanism to accommodate the increased lung volume. The barrel-shaped chest contributes to the typical appearance of patients with emphysema and is associated with the prolonged expiration and pursed-lip breathing seen in these patients. Chronic inhalation of irritants, most commonly tobacco smoke, is the primary cause of emphysema, leading to inflammatory changes, protease-antiprotease imbalance, and eventual destruction of alveolar structures.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 91.","responses":[{"text":"Lung cancer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Asthma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Emphysema","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic bronchitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary embolism","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15890,"text":"Which of the following corresponds to the total lung compliance of both lungs?","explanation":"The **total lung compliance** refers to the ease with which the lungs expand for a given change in the transpulmonary pressure. Total lung compliance for both lungs combined in a healthy adult is typically around **200 ml of air/cm H₂O**. This means that for every 1 cm H₂O increase in the transpulmonary pressure, the lungs will expand by 200 ml. Compliance can be affected by factors that influence the elasticity of the lungs (like the amount of elastin and collagen in the lung tissues) and the surface tension in the alveoli. Diseases such as emphysema can increase compliance, making the lungs too stretchy, while fibrosis can decrease compliance, making the lungs stiff.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 491.","responses":[{"text":"300 ml of air/cm H₂O","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"250 ml of air/cm H₂O","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"400 ml of air/cm H₂O","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"100 ml of air/cm H₂O","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"200 ml of air/cm H₂O","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15893,"text":"A child has difficulty breathing upon inhalation of pet dander dust and smoke. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"The child's symptoms of difficulty breathing upon exposure to specific triggers such as pet dander, dust, and smoke are indicative of **Atopic asthma**. Atopic asthma is a type of asthma that is triggered by allergens and is often associated with other allergic conditions like allergic rhinitis and atopic dermatitis. It is the most common form of asthma and usually starts in childhood. The condition involves an immune response in which IgE antibodies are produced in response to specific allergens. Upon exposure to these allergens, an inflammatory response is triggered in the bronchi, leading to bronchoconstriction, mucus production, and the characteristic symptoms of asthma such as wheezing, shortness of breath, and chest tightness.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 679.","responses":[{"text":"Lung cancer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nonatopic asthma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atopic asthma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Emphysema","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic bronchitis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15905,"text":"An 81-year-old patient is repetitively hospitalized due to respiratory tract infections. What of the following is the best advice that a doctor can give him to avoid future respiratory tract infections?","explanation":"The best advice a doctor can give an 81-year-old patient to avoid future respiratory tract infections is to receive the **Pneumococcal and influenza vaccine**. Elderly individuals are at an increased risk of complications from respiratory diseases like pneumonia and influenza. The Pneumococcal vaccine protects against infections caused by the bacterium Streptococcus pneumoniae, which can lead to pneumonia, meningitis, and bloodstream infections. Influenza vaccine, on the other hand, provides protection against the flu, a common respiratory illness with potential severe complications in older adults. While other measures like maintaining hygiene, proper diet, and specific vaccines have their own importance, for an elderly individual, the combined protection from Pneumococcal and influenza vaccine offers the most effective preventive approach against common respiratory tract infections.","reference":"(1) Dow lecture slides. Respiratory module-I; Subject: Community Medicine, Topic: Acute Respiratory Tract Infections.\r\n\r\n(2) Lieberman D, Lieberman D. Management of respiratory infections in the elderly. Expert Review of Anti-Infective Therapy. Published October 2003. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15482146/","responses":[{"text":"Pneumococcal and influenza vaccine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Washing hands and maintain hygiene","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adenovirus vaccine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Haemophilus influenza B vaccine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Proper diet","correct":false,"visible":false}]}
]

